Preferred items for Samson would be any damage item, some health increasing items, and guppy's paw, allowing him to keep soul hearts to increase his damage instead of having to replenish his red hearts.

Samson is the third of the easiest characters due to his starting item bloody lust, meaning that the first four hits he takes increases his power by .5(for the first one) and .33 (each of the second, third, and fourth times) on each floor.

Preferred items for Eve are Guppy's Paw (So that Eve can have one heart at all times), damage items (which is good for everyone), and Dark Bum (So you have less of an inclination to pick up a red heart).

Eve is the second of the easiest characters to play due to both dead bird and whore of babylon, specifically whore of Babylon and the effect it has on Eve. A single spike door is enough to activate the effect, and any damage that eve takes activates dead bird.

Preferred items for Azazel are anything that increased range or shot speed/tears (Such as Cancer or 8 Ball), Spoon Bender, and the Ludivico Technique. Brimstone, Ludivico Technique, And Spoon Bender is one of the most powerful combos in the game itself.
Azazel I have been told is quoted to be "The binding of Isaac character that people play in order to learn the movement of the enemies.) which is truthfully true.

Azazel, the first (and probably the top) of the three best of the characters, is the easiest to play. He starts with Brimstone and Flight, three black hearts (and heart containers can be used) and the fool card (which allows him to take absolutely no damage after a spike door
Preferred items for Eden depend on the kind of items that you start with.

Eden, (Although I have never played Eden), starts with completely random items, and one can not reset with Eden to get better items. Even if they have the Tick. And Eden requires Eden Tokens, and each time you start a new game with Eden you use one Token.
The preferred Items are... I don't know, maybe some extra health and damage? I don't know.

Judas starts with one red heart, 3 coins, and the book of Belial, and has an increased damage multiplier of .35 from base Isaac. This means Judas will die in two hits if he doesn't have an extra heart in normal mode, and if he does not get enough hearts, he will die by spike door

The preferred items (or the best items, your choice to decide), are Dark Bum (to pick up the red hearts and turn them into soul and evil hearts), Petrified Poop (only if you keep the spacebar so that you have increased chance for things), and some item that increases damage.

??? Starts with 3 Blue Hearts, the Poop spacebar item, and has the same exact stats as Isaac (Being the dead Isaac). However, every single item that increases health gives Blue Baby an additional Blue Heart. No Red hearts can be picked up, and all devil deals are three soul heart

This will be a feed, but perhaps an unpopular opinion of The Binding of Isaac: Rebirth, Afterbirth, and Afterbirth+ is that the three hardest at the start of playing them are Blue Baby (???), Judas, and Eden, and the three easiest characters likewise are Azazel, Eve, and Samson

On the topic of my last tweet (The Various versions of nightcore and the changes that're made in them), I think by far my favorite of the versions to make is Anti-Nightcore.

This also factors in Male and Female versions of songs, where Male Versions are female singer songs that are a decrease in pitch where a Female Version is a male singer song that has an increase in pitch.
Deep Nightcore increases the speed of the song by the percentages where the pitch is decreased, and it's opposite, Slow Nightcore, is a decrease in speed and an increase in pitch.

Nightcore itself is a positive increase in pitch and speed by anywhere between 15-25% while Anti-Nightcore, it's opposite as it it is a negative increase in pitch and speed from 15-40% (they would be negative in percent change)

So, that's just a rant/food for thought topic I just came up with completely on the spot. Thanks for taking the time to listen.

And that's why PvP games are played more and have a much larger audience, the factor of people wanting to win. In reality, video games should be played to have fun or to complete the story/achieve something that allows you to be at your highest sense of happiness.

There's also another thing, and this is an opinion based statement because I do not actually kniw the statistics, but more people play pvp- based games instead pve-based games, because a good chunk of people would rather win a game than have fun playing it.

And usually that's the downfall of many streamers, is just not having someone to talk to or someone to watch their chat and such. And it's starts to get to them after multiple times when it's low that they just aren't good at something.

But there's a lack of motivation to stream, usually because people continue to look at their viewer count as a small streamer and see 0-1 viewers and just feel like they aren't doing something right (and in terms of Xbox the damned bar(I really hate that bar Xbox please remove))
On Xbox and PS4, it's a mic at least (Now I'll say this I don't have a preference for platforms because they're all good).

This spectrum is a thing that unmotivates people and it's a mindset that a lot of people have about what a streamer should have. On pc it is good quality, a mic, webcam (which is optional as well), a good keyboard, mouse, all of the basic gamer/streamer equipment
And yeah, that applies to the whole requirement for Youtube Partnership/Twitch Partnership/Twitch Affiliate, but that applies to a bigger spectrum so to say.

However, majority of people lose interest and motivation (myself included) and just stop trying to pursue Twitch and Youtube(not myself included). And there's a series of set reasons as to why. One major thing, as I can think of, is the "Requirements"

Well, a vast majority of people also have a whole ideal/dream of making it big as a Twitch Streamer or a Youtuber, and only a good percentage of people actually make it to the point where they can do twitch and youtube full time.

So this is a message thread I just thought of all on the spot, and it's kind of stressing to think about. So we all have the major video platforms Twitch and Youtube, right? Where anyone can stream on twitch and anyone can post videos and stream on youtube.
